## Database URL
When connecting to a database, we must use various database-specific parameters. Such as host names, port numbers, database names, login credentials, etc.

## Connection
```java
String url = "jdbc:postgresql:COREJAVA";
String username = "dbuser";
String password = "secret";
Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, username, password);
```
The driver manager iterates through the registered drivers to find a driver that can use the sub-protocol specified in the database URL.

## ResultSet
When we execute a query, we are interested in the result. The executeQuery object returns an object of type ResultSet that we can use to walk through the result one row at a time.
```java
ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM Books");
```

The basic loop for analyzing a result set looks like this:
```java
while (rs.next()) {
look at a row of the result set
}
```

## Query execution

## Prepared Statement
Whenever the database executes a query, it first computes a strategy of how to do it efficiently. By preparing the query and reusing it, we ensure that the planning step is done only once.
```java
String publisherQuery =
"SELECT Books.Price, Books.Title " +
"FROM Books, Publishers " +
"WHERE Books.Publisher_Id = Publishers.Publisher_Id AND Publishers.Name = ?";
PreparedStatement stat = con.prepareStatement(publisherQuery);
```
Before executing the prepared statement, the host variables must be binded to actual values.

## ResultSet Metadata
ResultSetMetaData, reports information about a result set. Whenever we have a result set from a query, we can inquire about the number of columns and each columns name, type, and field width.
```java
ResultSet rs = stat.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM " + tableName);
ResultSetMetaData meta = rs.getMetaData();
for (int i = 1; i <= meta.getColumnCount(); i++) {
String columnName = meta.getColumnLabel(i);
int columnWidth = meta.getColumnDisplaySize(i);
. . .
}
```
